  <p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> 
  <p>It’s not just the nature of tasks that shapes AI’s impact; how we use AI also matters. Developers who incorporate AI into their workflow might more frequently refine their approach, learning when and how to leverage it most effectively. Early interactions with AI might be limited to basic code suggestions, but over time, developers might integrate it into more nuanced problem-solving, documentation, and debugging efforts. As their familiarity grows, so too does AI’s perceived value. The data reflects this: Developers who use AI more often tend to report stronger productivity benefits (see figure 3).</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>From Assistant to Agent (and the Limits of Autonomy)</h4> 
  <p>The industry has moved toward agentic AI tools that can plan multi-step changes, execute commands, and modify files across a project. The parallelism of multi-agent systems offers the promise of even greater productivity growth.</p> 
  <p>However, recent qualitative research from Sara Chizari at Microsoft suggests this momentum may be outpacing how developers actually work. In a controlled study of eight experienced developers, most chose not to run multiple agents at once, even under time pressure. Cognitive load, the need for explicit context boundaries, and a preference for finishing tasks end to end all limited concurrency. Rather than leaning into automation, developers leaned into control, deliberately introducing checkpoints and using planning modes to inspect the agent’s intent before authorizing action.</p> 
  <p>The strongest predictor of success in multi-agent sessions was not tool capability but specification quality. Sessions with clear decomposition and defined roles succeeded; sessions without upfront structure produced conflicting outputs and what developers described as “merge nightmares.” Multi-agent AI does not create structure; it exposes whether structure already exists. These findings extend the task-complexity story: It is not only that AI struggles with complex tasks, but that developer cognitive capacity for overseeing AI has limits, too.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3807964/assets/html/houck_fig3.svg" alt="Figure 3. Response to question, “Which best describes how often you use AI tools in your day-to-day work?” compared with the average agreement rating to the question, “Using AI helps me to be more productive.”" /> 
  <br /> <span style="font-size:0.8em;">Figure 3. Response to question, “Which best describes how often you use AI tools in your day-to-day work?” compared with the average agreement rating to the question, “Using AI helps me to be more productive.”</span> 
  <p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Frequency of Use Shapes Perceived Value</h4> 
  <p>The data suggests a positive relationship between AI usage frequency and how strongly developers believe it improves their productivity. This trend alone, however, does not imply causation. Relatively small sample sizes for less frequent AI users mean the differences are not statistically significant, so they could have arisen by chance. The direction of the relationship also remains unclear: Does frequent AI use lead to greater productivity, or are developers who already see value in AI simply more likely to use it more often?</p>
  <p>Our observational studies of professional Java developers provide additional insights. Success with AI depends on three key factors:</p>
  <p>– Task complexity</p>
  <p>– Developer skill</p>
  <p>– Familiarity with AI</p>
  <p>AI works well for routine tasks but struggles with novel problems. More experienced developers evaluate AI-generated code more effectively, and those familiar with how LLMs work are better at refining prompts and integrating AI into workflows.</p>
  <p>Developers engage in a continuous loop when working with AI: formulating the problem, determining inputs, evaluating AI suggestions, and deciding on implementation.</p>
  <p>Breakdowns at any step—misunderstanding the task, unclear prompts, or lack of trust in AI outputs—can lead to frustration and wasted effort. Many developers say working with AI requires new skills or forces them to engage skills they don’t often use. A distinguished engineer at Microsoft described this learning curve:</p> 
  <div style="margin-left:24pt;">
   <p>“[GitHub Copilot Chat] took me a long time to use because I felt like Chat is for when I’m not in [coding] flow. That was not a muscle that I had at all.”</p>
  </div>
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Teamwide Adoption Amplifies Impact</h4>
  <p>AI’s impact isn’t just about how it is used; it’s also shaped by the people around you. The way AI is adopted within a team can influence how individuals perceive its value, whether through shared best practices, cultural norms, or simply seeing colleagues benefit from its use. The next section explores how teamwide AI adoption affects perceptions of productivity.</p>
  <p>As shown in table 2, developers working on teams where AI is widely adopted are more likely to view their team as productive. This follows, logically, from the strong agreement developers have that AI makes them more productive. It stands to reason that the more of their peers who use this productivity-boosting tool, the more productive the team will be. This raises an important question about whether there will be growing social pressure to adopt AI if the absence of adopting it will make individuals seem less productive in the eyes of their peers.</p> 
